<HEADLINE>
<P>
MERRITT'S HEAVE PUTS RIVALS THROUGH HOOPS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JOHN ORTEGA, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Darvena Merritt of North Hollywood High earned All-City Section 4-A Division 
honors in basketball last season, but she won't be shooting hoops for some time 
if she continues to put the shot like she did in Friday's Valley Pac-8 
Conference track and field finals at Birmingham High. 
</P>
<P>
 The fourth-place finisher in the City championships as a sophomore, Merritt 
improved her personal best to 37 feet 4 inches as a junior last year and was 
regarded as the front-runner for the City title until she broke two fingers on 
her throwing hand in a pickup basketball game. 
</P>
<P>
 "After making it to City as a sophomore, I really wanted to win it all last 
year," said Merritt, who won the Pac-8 title Friday with a heave of 42-0. "But 
the injury ended my season." 
</P>
<P>
 Merritt has converted that disappointment into motivation and it has paid off. 
She cracked the 40-foot barrier last month and set a personal best on Friday. 
</P>
<P>
 It was the best mark by a City athlete since Erin McConahey of Van Nuys put 
the shot 42-2 3/4 in 1989. "I had no idea about the shotput when I started two 
years ago," Merritt admitted. "But once I started competing, I began to get 
more serious. . . . Basketball had always been the No. 1 sport with me, but I 
like track more than basketball now." 
</P>
<P>
 Merritt also placed second in the triple jump (32-10 1/4) and ran a leg on 
North Hollywood's second-place 400-meter relay team (52.4 seconds) as the top 
five finishers in each event qualified for Thursday's City preliminaries. 
</P>
<P>
 Birmingham, second in last year's City championships, won eight of 15 events 
in the boys' meet, led by James Lincoln's three victories and Marvin Powell's 
two. 
</P>
<P>
 Lincoln, a senior, was upset by Powell in the 110 high hurdles, 15.1 to 15.4, 
to start the meet, but he rebounded with victories in the high jump (6-2), long 
jump (personal best of 22-2 3/4) and triple jump (43-10). 
</P>
<P>
 Powell, a junior, added a victory in the 300 intermediate hurdles with a 
personal best of 41.5. 
</P>
<P>
 Monroe's Jose Padilla ran 4 minutes 27 seconds in the 1,600 and 9:48.7 in the 
3,200 to easily win those events. 
</P>
</TEXT>
